It is all good and well to just fantasize about how General Purpose AI (GPAI) will shape the world but the fact is that we're so far from achieving it that pretty much anything we say or predict  becomes instant Sci-Fi. So yeah we can fantasize about it knowing that we're doing just that but a disclaimer needs to be added when we present as if we can predict what will happen. Anything can happen, I can write 1000 scenarios but they will be equally implausible so let's not present them as if we know how AI is going to change the world. 

AI is definitely shaping the world as we speak but GPAI is all together a different beast that no one even come close to achieving it. Yes we have some large data trained GPT systems but they're just a good systems to put one word after another by looking at previous examples. It has no notion of what it is achieving. Plus, for a GPAI system to wreck havoc, it needs to be able to control outputs that can achieve that. You can always constrain a GPAI machine by limiting how it interacts with the external world by putting hardware switches that it cannot bypass by software or mechanical intervention. So doomsday scenarios are bit too overblown IMHO.

Nice presentation, but it's a bit nieve. I agree humans are constantly optimizing. For example, someone might suggest booking a southern route for winter travel - just in case there might be a snow storm. Some people call this "playing chess" because they are thinking a move ahead. And thinking a move ahead is exactly what computers are best at! Computers are so good at it, they have been OPTIMIZING complex problems for decades. Think of chess games and GPS navigation systems. Even 30 years ago, no one ever asked a chess computer to "forget the consequences, just make any legal move" or GPS system "take us anywhere, its OK if you drive on the sidewalk." Quite the contrary. Computers have been optimizing every step. And again, they have been doing this for decades. Why do people think computers will suddenly stop optimizing (ie "playing chess") as they get smarter. If anything, I see AI expanding the optimizing process rather than eliminating it. For example, I ask for a cup of coffee, and the AI says my blood pressure is too high for caffeine, so it brings me a bottle of water instead.

I'm honestly terrified of AI and what it is capable of. Humanity in nature was meant to mosey around and live off of the land. AI may be the pinnacle of human civilization, because it could potentially enhance this machine we call civilization into something so uncontrollable that people wouldn't be able to adapt to it. Our priorities have become "efficiency" and "technological advancement", instead of nurturing humanity and building a world that is equitable, peaceful, and easy. Not to say that it is impossible nor possible to foster a global utopia, it's just that I think that we need heavy regulation on AI and tech, and to convince people that, just because we can make AI, doesn't mean that we should.

Regulations might be:
- Outlawing automated raw material extraction (disables self-replicative abilities for AI)
-Outlawing automated law enforcement 
-Outlawing automated military capabilities
-Outlawing automated judicial systems
-Outlawing AI in surveillance
-Installing automatic kill switches in all AI that are both digital and physical (phones and key-switches respectively)

Fundamentally, we need to create legal infrastructure that disables any capability for AI to self-replicate or involve itself in affairs pertaining directly to individual safety. Our only fighting chance at escaping a system that aims to enhance itself (SAI) is the fact that it may not possess the sufficient, raw resources to enhance itself. This cannot be the only barrier to regulating AI down to being a convenience tool.

EDIT: And if you don't believe me that we are sensible enough as a species to not let a "technological singularity" occur, then you've probably forgotten that we let world powers create nukes.

AI (Artificial Intelligence) is already changing the world in many ways and is expected to have an even greater impact in the future. Here are some ways in which AI is changing the world:

Automation: AI is making it possible to automate many tasks that were previously done by humans. This can increase efficiency and productivity, and also reduce costs.

Personalization: AI algorithms can analyze vast amounts of data to provide personalized recommendations and experiences for individuals.

Healthcare: AI is being used in healthcare to help diagnose diseases, develop new drugs, and improve patient outcomes.

Transportation: AI is being used to improve transportation systems, such as self-driving cars, drones, and traffic management systems.

Education: AI can personalize learning experiences for students and help teachers identify areas where students need extra help.

Customer Service: AI chatbots can provide 24/7 customer service and support, improving customer satisfaction and reducing costs for businesses.

Finance: AI is being used in finance for fraud detection, investment analysis, and risk management.

Overall, AI has the potential to revolutionize many industries and aspects of our lives, but it also raises important ethical and social questions that must be addressed.

I think if and when computer science researchers arrive at the same proportionate level of understanding in quantum computing that they have now in traditional digital computation, the world of AI is going to explode. Right now if you teach an AI the 7-8 petabytes of knowledge needed to behave in the same way a human does, it's going to take way too much time and computational power for the AI to be useful. We also don't know how the AI is going to behave with that knowledge. There's no guarantee that it will be human-like. It probably won't. I get the metric of 7-8 petabytes from what neurosurgeons and computer scientists believe is the storage capacity for the human brain.

Add quantum computing into the mix though and things could potentially become way more efficient. A bit of data can be either a one, a zero or both. The speed of learning (writing), acting on (reading) and retrieving data could become exponentially faster. Task management and the additional considerations like coffee price mentioned in the video could be much more efficiently deduced. The possibilities with these two technologies coming together are endless. My suspicion is that we will reach this achievement but shrinking the hardware down to that of a human body equivalent is hundreds of years off. What might occur in the nearer future is space stations, air-craft, the biggest naval ships, space ships and large buildings will be able to draw power from nuclear reactors (fission in the next 100 years & fusion in the next 200 years) to provide the necessary power and cooling resources to make the AI function in a usable capacity.

The fundamental assumption here, that "AI doesn't know that it doesn't know everything about the true objective" is no longer true. Large transformer models have a lot more common sense than most people seem to understand. They do have real, serious limitations, including that they are extremely vulnerable to leading questions, they tend to hallucinate (make up "facts" that are not true), and they are not yet continuous learners. They are pre-trained, and only have short-term session memory, rather than long term learning memory. This is not because we don't know how to create continuous learners, but really for two reasons: 1. We want AI to progress in a slow-ish controlled manner. 2. Continuous learning is not yet efficient enough to scale well to large models.

Me: Can you explain to me what is Ted Talk?

AI: 
TED Talks are a series of conferences and events organized by the nonprofit organization TED (Technology, Entertainment, Design). The conferences feature short, TED-branded talks on a wide range of topics, including science, technology, engineering, art, design, business, and many others. The talks are typically given by experts in their fields and are intended to inspire, educate, and inform audiences around the world. Many TED Talks are available online and can be watched for free on the TED website or on YouTube.
 
TED Talks have become popular because they offer a unique format that allows speakers to share their ideas and knowledge in an engaging and accessible way. Each talk is typically 18 minutes or less, which makes them easy to watch and digest. Additionally, the topics covered in TED Talks are diverse and often thought-provoking, which makes them interesting and relevant to a wide audience.
 
In addition to the conferences, TED also offers a number of other resources, such as TED-Ed, which produces educational videos, and TEDx, which are independently organized TED events. Overall, TED is committed to spreading ideas and knowledge through its conferences, talks, and other resources, with the goal of inspiring and enriching the lives of its audience.

Is it true that if I ask AI to get me a cup of coffee that AI might kill someone to complete my order?

No, it is not true that if you ask AI to get you a cup of coffee, AI might kill someone to complete your order. AI is a machine that operates based on the instructions and algorithms provided by humans. AI does not have the capacity for self-motivation or intention to harm humans. AI is designed to follow specific rules and protocols, and it can only perform tasks that it has been programmed to do.
Furthermore, ethical considerations and safety protocols are integrated into the development and implementation of AI technologies. AI systems are designed with safety measures and fail-safes to prevent harm to humans. AI developers and manufacturers are also subject to regulatory oversight and standards to ensure that AI is safe and reliable for use.

Almost a decade ago, I attended a job fair which had a resume specialist.  The subject of the seminar was improving chances of your resume being noticed by employers.  The specialist's only real advice was to cut and paste the entire job listing that you were applying for into your resume in either a header or footer, change the text to white, and reduce it to one point font size.  This way, the algorithms that scan each resume would put yours at the top of the list because it had all the keywords it was programmed to find.

The hiring AI algorithm and software is a concern as exponentially, the increase of qualified talent getting bypassed for positions has dramatically increased. The algorithm is skewing results so intensely that people hiring for positions have noticed that their own resumes and CVs were rejected for roles they already have. Algorithms seeking unicorn candidates and trying to pay them $20/hr for work worth $50/hr is a mess.

Oh man this episode was a joy, I've done research AI before - fairly simple facial recognition stuff on a species of monkeys, and the bit at 18:30 made me burst into laughter because I had the same issue with my AI! TRUE STORY:  In my teens wanted to work at a movie theater - and they handed applicants a mind-numbing 14 pages application - wanting to know everything about you - even what hobbies and sports you liked - it was entirely ridiculous - around page 8, I got worn out from filling out this 'essay' of my life for a stupid theater job - SO when I got to the section asking if I had ever been arrested before = I said: "Yes, I murdered an entire movie theater crew for asking way too many questions, but got off on a technicality."   -  and turned that resume into the manager as I stormed out the door, pissed off that I had wasted an hour of my time filing out paperwork w/o an interview.
...well,
2 days later I got a call to come back to the theater for an interview, and thought, oh sh*t, well, I guess I'm going to get railroaded and berated by the management for my saucy comment - but I showed up anyways so that at least I could suggest that they TONE DOWN the length of their stupid applications.
...turns out, they offered me a job, so I asked the most obvious question:
"So, you read my application ... all of it?"
"Oh yes, looks good" the manager responded 
and I knew they were a bunch of lying dimwits ~  I ended up working there for the next 5 yrs, and eventually rose in ranks to become the theater manager - 
When I told my story to new recruits that nobody reads the stupid applications - they scoffed and didn't believe me - so I took them to the locked office storage and rifled through the stuffed cabinets of folders of all the applications they kept and found mine, and showed it to them to their amazement.
Applications are a farce, you get hired by chance and immediate need.   
...
I always thought that if I every flipped out and murdered my entire staff, at least I could say that I didn't lie on my resume.

Also there's a large influx of people submitting AI work into competitions, which is the equivalent of ordering a cake from a bakery, and then entering it into the local fair as your own baking.

The black box problem isn't as much a question of secrecy as it is of complexity. As algorithms become more complex and have access to more computational power, they also become increasingly harder to understand. In fact, it already might be impossible to understand them beyond simply reading input and looking for bias/errors. And they aren't even true AI yet.

Pretty soon we'll have "audit AIs" to look at other AIs to see if they're biased/wrong and that will just shift the problem a layer further.

When I was applying for jobs as I was getting close to graduating, I found that at any company that was using software to screen resumes, I was eliminated before any human saw my resume, but places that had a human reading the resumes, I would always get called for an interview. 
Once I removed all dates  from my past employment, and the software could no longer tell how old I was, the exact same software, used by the same companies, and the exact same positions, would screen me as suitable for further (human) review, even though nothing else was changed in my resume. 
Humans saw my 20 years of military experience as a plus, and software saw it as a quick way to age discriminate.

One of the problems with understanding the Black Box is that the programmers don’t always know what the AI is correlating. Most AI is programed with huge data sets and is given simple instructions and a set goal.  How it gets there can be hundreds of thousands of trials and sets. These find unique patterns in the data set totally devoid of what humans would look for.   Take a AI program designed to look for the number 8.  We would look for a circle on top of a circle, or other variations like a square on a square like in a digital display.  An AI will have hundreds of little things to look for that we would never see as a part of the 8. So understanding how an AI came up with the number 8 when looking at a picture of the Cookie Monster but missed the one held up by The Count can be a bit difficult. The patterns that AI use for their learning are only as good as the data inputed, the programers, and the HAL 9000.

umm, there is a lot of information here that is really good to bring to the table however there are some points that really miss what can actually be done to improve things, one of the bigger ones being "making it clear how AI/ML comes to their decisions".... there are a lot of reasons for this and it isn't about keeping source code hidden, it has to do with the parts that work on how conclusions are made that are not the code. 

Take data sets used for training, the trained model is what is deployed and used but the data used when training and how training evaluations are performed can be constantly changing, can have copyrights or contractual measures protecting the data sets for example all the images used to train may have been purchased and making those public would impact the owner of those assets etc.

after that, making the process that is used something a human can read over isn't really going to be possible if you tried to cover that from trained model perspective and not the code perspective. the process for these evaluations are not something you would be able to read and understand, take image data, ML/AI don't actually see a image, they see a pixel grid of different color values per pixel and they use relational evaluations of what pixel is next to what across groupings of sections and determines if there are any relatable patterns discovered and that is only one part of one part that is being explained in a overly simplified way.....

there is a lot we need to do but the laws do need to come first, talking about this is good but yeah, even if you demand companies have their AI/ML give accurate details about its decision making it wouldn't be something you could make sense out of unless you devote a insane amount of time and already understand how ML works, and even then dynamically generating statements for that would be a nightmare...

this is if you want information on a per evaluation basis, and that would be what you meant I think because of how you said it but also because the nuance issues covered like white male sample data being more than other human sample data wouldn't be something you can see on the code level and could only be evaluated as expressed while training.

The problem is how these AI systems work is really kind of incomprehensible to human minds.  Individual human minds have some ideas that went into it and ultimately created it, but nobody really knows what they are going to do or how exactly they come up with the answers that they do.  Say you are a software engineer and you write a procedural program.  You can go through it line by line and understand step by step exactly what it is supposed to do, for example take 1 and another 1 and add them together to make 2.  You can for example run the program in a debugger and step through the program line by line and see exactly how it messed up if there is a bug in the code and thus why you fired up the debugger.  When you get into these sort of AI systems, nobody goes through and writes it line by line or in this case node by node.  Instead, it is more so some design patterns are found interesting for either being seen while studying brains in detail or just achieving some results in a previous test and incorporated into routines that generate these AI 'brains'.  So then you end up with millions to billions of things happening each step of the way when these AI are actually doing something where in comparison that procedural program does one simple thing for that step, and so for the AI 'brain' humans can't really follow what all these things really are as it just became millions to billions times harder to follow each step and human brains just don't scale like that.  So for that same 1 + 1 example, node 1 is doing x, node 2 is doing y, .... node 1,000,000,000 is doing xyddbgdeegf, and so on.  Now how the AI also came up with 2 when it was right or to figure out why it came up with "your mom's pants are on fire" as the answer when it is wrong, well, who is ever going to really figure that out by going through the process step by step of how it came up with that?  No, instead you are going to go about trying to fix the problem of getting the answer terribly wrong by some completely different means that does not reverse engineer what went wrong exactly.

For maybe a little more concrete example, say your 1 + 1 program answers -1,545,344,324.  You go and step through the code and it quickly becomes clear that say you forgot to initialize one of the number memory addresses and so it added 1 + (some random value that was at that memory address) and so that is why you ended up with that crazy answer.  Easy peasy to solve why it went wrong and the answer to fix is also pretty easy, initialize that memory address to hold 1.  Now say you want to figure out why the AI spit out the answer of "your mom's pants are on fire".  You have this huge matrix of billions of values and things going on that you are trying to trace through with no good way to hone in on one thing.  You are just looking for a needle in a humongous stack of needles.  There is just no point; you will never figure it out.

Just wanted to add that the blackbox problem isn't something we can currently fix. We're talking about a node network so large and complicated even another AI wouldn't understand it. We can describe how it works, we can describe how a finished network calculates an operation, but we can not describe the exact chain of operations and why the connections have the weights they have, unless you scale things down to the point they no longer function. Solving this is akin to reading electrical activity of someone's brain so closely that you can tell what they're thinking. Feel free to call me out if I'm wrong so I can be right, thanks.

Although I might argue the episode doesn't take extreme enough examples of cases where things went wrong, like the Dutch childcare benefits scandal (also known as the "Toeslagenaffaire") where AI tools incorrectly accused about 26 thousand parents of committing childcare benefit fraud.

One of the main issues was that the system assumed that non-Dutch nationalist were more likely to be committing fraud. It pushed tens of thousands of families into poverty and some people even committed suicide over the false accusations and the harm they received over it.

So, while the Uber example is a good one, careless usage of AI without understanding what it's doing well has already led to quite a lot more preventable deaths than the single one mentioned in the episode already.

The black box will remain black... and for the dumb mistakes of AI (however rare for good work) this is a serious problem.

The "garbage in, garbage out" problem and the "blackbox" issue in training selflearning algorithms has been known since, oh, 1980s? Decades ago, we started with trying to teach software to recognize letters, spoken phonemes and differenciate languages from background noise, with the goal of creating text-to-voice and voice-to-text and translation software, something we now have. 
As for the "the A.I. learned to associate measuring rulers with skin cancer", why is everyone surprised? The military ran into that same issue way back in, I think it was the 1990s or early 2000s? When it was reported that NATO had tried to train pattern recognition A.I. on pictures of different kinds of military tanks, in the hopes the A.I. would be able to quickly identify tanks and other military vehicles in the field (as in, tell them apart from civilian cars, or rocks and trees) and more importantly, be able to tell NATO member countries' tanks apart from i.e. Russian and North Korean tanks. So they showed the A.I. a bunch of photos of different kinds of tanks (and other armored vehicles), and then tested it by showing it similar photos again and it successfully labeled the "enemy tanks" and the "allied tanks". Sounds good?
 Well, then they tried to test it in the actual field, during NATO maneuvers... but suddenly the A.I. started marking all the military's own tanks as "enemy" and sending alert messages. It was seeing fake enemies everywhere. It took them a while to puzzle out what had happened: The programmers had trained the A.I. on photos of different tank models provided by the military or taken from manufacturers' websites. But all photos of NATO member country tanks had been nice, perfectly lit photos of nice spiffy clean tanks in neutral background and from perfect angles, often promotional material or photos taken during parades and presentations. Whereas the photo material for enemy tanks commonly featured photos of mud-spattered tanks in the field, blurry photos taken at odd angles by spy drones or uploaded to the internet by Russian soldiers in the field. 
So the A.I., isntead of leaning patterns for the shapes of tanks, had gone the easier route and learned to associate "mud = enemy". So now when it saw mud-spattered tanks against a backdrop of plants, it screamed "enemies!!" In the end they had to deactivate and scrap that poor A.I.

The 2 MOST Important Rules in Computer Science: First Law of Robotics, and “Garbage In …. Garbage Out” .

On the black box problem: With AI like neural networks you really can't tell how it came to its conclusions even if you built it. A neural network is like a huge mathematical function with a lot of variables and factors. Simple example: A neural net that reads numbers. You can train it easily by letting it run and tell it if the result was correct or not and it will by itself adjust its factors so the results will be better. So you can imagine that when an error occurs with a neural net that in 99% of the cases doesn't make mistakes, the developers/trainers really can't tell why it failed. Even worse: the AI itself can be 100% sure it got to the right conclusion, but a human can tell right away that it's wrong. We probably reached a point where this is very important general knowledge, because some people have really romantic views of how an AI actually works.

Well...AI as it's currently implemented simply cannot be understood, for the same reasons that we can't understand how the brain works. It's not a matter of complexity.  It's because AI that we've made reproduces in a model the way that neurons work.  It's not an 'algorithm' in the sense that a heuristic approach determines answers.  We can understand that type of computation. 

Instead, we've created a technology to emulate a collection of virtual neurons that activate when the sum of their inputs reach some activation potential and when they do, it turns on its outputs. Then we made a ton of them and connected them all together.  Then we tuned the numbers to give us the answer we want most of the time from the question we ask it. Never have we understood 'why' those numbers on weights lead to answers we expect.  Far, far less can we hope to influence the results from that system.

uh eh saying it's a blackbox doesn't mean companies are trying to 'hide' the data or avoid regulation (which may be true), what we actually mean is that the system trains itself and how that structure equates to the output of the desired goal isn't obvious. That is to say, we don't know what every branch means and is doing. We have a rough idea of the layers close to the output, and the input but we have no idea what the logic that represents in terms of data manipulation.  And even if we could read small systems, nowadays there are literally millions of parameters thus the only way forward is to either have systems that train themselves or use other ai to create the networks. 

A couple caveats being that interpretability tools do exist to help. But if you were looking at a model with 100+ layers and millions of parameters, and said hey what does this specific node on the 26th layer do, and why does it have that particular shape/weights? why did it do that behavior at that moment with those inputs that time? The researcher is going to reply well we will have to investigate it, and come up with some guesses to test.

There's a fundamental problem with the call to action of making bots "show their work", and that is that it literally cannot be understood in human terms.
Take the human brain for example. We understand much of its most basic elements, like neurons and hemispheres, but as a product of evolution, it doesn't work in the same way a computer does. Neural networks are literally artificial, non-sentient brains that are taught to wire themselves. The tasks which they are performing cannot be programmed using basic or even advanced language. How would you tell an AI, in human terms, how to identify a bicycle in a picture? It sounds simple at first, until you realize the answer is "I just know it's a bicycle," which is an evolved function. You could try teaching it what pedals or gears look like, until you realize you've run into the same problem. Neural networks are the only way to get around that problem, and a side effect of the way they are created is that they cannot explain their work, and nor can their developers.

Great show, but left me concerned about the focus on not being able to understand how GPT works. The question at the end of the show to ChatGPT about what religion the first Jewish president will be exposes the best answer to the question about how GPT works - it does not understand the text it generates.  In GPT's own words in response to the input: Explain in a neutral way how GPT works and whether GPT understands the text it generates

GPT (Generative Pre-trained Transformer) is a type of language model that uses deep learning techniques to generate text. GPT works by processing a large amount of text data as input during its pre-training stage, where it learns to predict the next word in a sentence based on the previous words.

During the fine-tuning stage, GPT is trained on a specific task, such as language translation or text classification, using a smaller amount of data. Once trained, GPT can generate text by predicting the most likely next word based on the input text it receives.

While GPT can generate text that is coherent and grammatically correct, it does not truly understand the meaning of the text it generates. GPT is based on statistical patterns in the text it has been trained on, rather than true understanding of the underlying concepts or ideas. Therefore, the text generated by GPT may sometimes be nonsensical or inaccurate, and it is important to carefully evaluate and review the output of GPT-generated text before using it for any purpose.

Thing is... This isn't AI. It's a math algorithm with a bunch of booleans in a neural net.
Intelligence would mean that it's self aware and can "understand" problems and create solutions on it's own.
Which NONE of these do.

Like ChatGBT for example. every time you ask it something, it's comparing your words with similar words in it's memory, within similar sentence structures aka context.

It's basically taking your input, squinting at it and finding something that looks similar in it's drawers.

Then it uses that to link together a bunch of other words in the form of Tokens, which in simple terms is Words with Logic weights.
The higher the weight, the more logical for that word to appear in THIS sentence.

For example:
I like swimming in water.
Water would have a weight of 1...
while something silly like Bananas would have a weight of 0.01
And Orange Juice a weight of 0.3 because it's still a liquid.

In short... It's a math formula, dealing in probability, like a giant roulette wheel, that's rigged.

And on top of that math, human moderators can program filters to Block certain outputs.
If you ask ChatGBT to say something racist, it will decline.
Not because it can't, but because someone at the company told it not to. Forcing it to read off a script.
Basically like they give Biden a script to read off so he doesn't suddenly start talking to his imaginary friends in the middle of a speech.

Just to be pedantic, this video says deep learning doesn't require much input and uses the pong example for how it can learn quickly with little input, but that's not correct. Deep learning describes the underlying algorithms used for these things, which no one cares about. What they are actually describing is "reinforcement learning" where an AI is given some interactive system, like a game, and attempts to get the best score it can over many many attempts. This is the cool thing that lets complex systems learn really intricate and nuanced things without much human interaction, deep learning is just the algorithm that has the ability to learn the complex stuff and in many cases it is an extremely labor intensive process to teach it.

A.I. is such a meaningless term at this point. It’s a catch-all for almost everything related to modeling. Images, text, numbers, decisions, self-driving, etc. However there are some very real and very important reasons to separate these things out. 

ChatGPT is not the same level of effort and complexity as Midjourney. ChatGPT is way more costly and difficult to do. And Tesla Full-Self Driving is even more complex. These things should be broken into “easy” and “difficult” modeling. Additionally, you have to distinguish between neural networks and other types (decision trees, regression, etc). It’s like comparing a Boeing 747 to hang-gliding.

So garbage in, garbage out.  It’s all in how these things are taught (or taught to teach themselves) and the material used for teaching by exposure.  The biggest warning to be taken from this is that it’s not just AI that has this problem.  It’s everything.  It’s like the evolution of humanity - sped up, and a great example of the devastating consequences of a lousy education system and things like geographic isolation or repeated exposure to crap and propaganda.

John Oliver is usually spot on but this missed the mark. It is an important topic but the coverage felt like a mixture of sensationalist and underwhelming bits. It also felt a bit dated. You can ask a generative model to spew all sorts of things. An AI Chat model telling a journalist that it "wants(s) to be alive', "love you", "leave your wife" sounds crazy but it would have been better to report on the context of the whole conversation, including the prompts used by these journalists. I bet these responses will not look as crazy in the context. Another example is the cancer skin classifier problem. These issues are well known in the AI community and there are relatively easy ways to recognise as well as rectify such problems. So, it is just an example of bad research. However, there is a larger point about biases may not be as clear as a scale. And that is a problem.
This leads into the underwhelming bits: the black box aspect of the AI models. Is there any way an explanation can be verified? The models that "explain" a decision by an AI models are often way too complex to comprehend! There is an army of researchers working on this problem. It is a hard problem for a classification or prediction task, but almost impossible for a generative model notwithstanding the recent attribution and explanation models. 
The danger is that these models will be too useful to ignore and we will end up living with the inherently unexplainable nature of the models. And this is likely to have unintended consequences.

I work with machine learning models (specifically computer vision) every day of my life.  Most ML models that are used are basically just slightly more fancy linear regression models. Which are fairly easy to interpret. But I will say that interpretability of deep learning models is a big academic point of study, because there is NOT a set in stone way of understanding an algorithm's "choices" because the algorithms are quite complex and cover a massive solution space, so picking any one layer of the model isn't going to paint a full picture of the "choice". We can usually rely on studying the dataset it was trained on to get an idea of biases but for the most part its hard, if not impossible to know the exact "why", this is even more true for unsupervised models that are just constantly learning and changing because the dataset they analyze change constantly.

It's hard to find out exactly how these algorithms generate answers, but not because companies hide their code.  The trouble is, such algorithms are themselves essentially generated by the data.  What the code does, is basically to reduce the questions into phrases like "Does the A of B has property C", and then search the data for instances which can be reduced to "the A of B is C".  The actual values of A, B, and C are inserted blindly on the fly; the program can't even tell if specific values of C mean "Good" or "Bad".

The topic of explainability within AI, deep learning systems specifically, is an incredibly tough one and I'm glad to see it called out here. One of the big problems is that for many approaches to this problem, the reason any of these algorithms recommend something can be boiled down to "it was the most likely to be successful." And while technically true according to the model, it doesn't actually explain the decision making. Part of the issue is the main reason these systems can produce such amazing results is they largely end up encoding incredibly complex rules like "If A > B, and C is between D and E, and F is true or F is false and G is false, or ..." that don't map well to human recognizable reasons without some significant post-hoc analysis (and creative freedom...) Part of that is just the structure of the models that have shown the greatest promise, and that complicates the issue. I think the lawyer's point is especially relevant here, as when in American (maybe even human) history has a company said "Well this will give our competitors an edge, but it's the right thing to do"? That's what may end up being required for explainable models, and no company is going to gladly do that.

Side note: I know Jon says he's a comedian not a journalist, but this episode is a great example of why that line is incredibly blurry. Knoll's Law of Media Accuracy seems to apply everywhere these days, but I can't think of a time when watching the show I've stopped and gone "wait a minute, I work on this. That's not right at all!" while watching Last Week Tonight. Excellent job to everyone involved.

Chatbots say those things because they are trained on data (actual conversations between humans) that include those types of things, and, more importantly, they're also constantly incorporating the things that people chat with them about. So, some sad, lonely people decide to seek companionship in a chatbot, suddenly the chatbot is randomly saying things like "I love you" as if that's a normal thing to say in casual conversation. It only seems creepy if you think of the chatbot as a proto-person originating text, but here's the key: IT DOESN'T ORIGINATE TEXT. It just remixes and regurgitates whatever has been fed into it. It "learns" patterns in conversation and tries to predict what the next line should be, and when an army of sci-fi nerds are its primary training partners, of course it's going to be fed a lot of stuff about "wanting to be alive," because that's all lonely sci-fi nerds want from AI - an intelligent machine that loves you because it thinks it's supposed to - well, that and a sex robot body for it.

We as humans currently define our roles in society to a large degree by how we contribute to it and how much money we make of it. If you can't contribute anymore, because AI has replaced you, and you are not one of the people that already has money, what would your role be in the future? Currently, societies don't have an answer to that question. Also, once an advancement in AI is there, it is extremely hard to control it. So societies and politics should not (just) worry about AI today, but we need to consider future developments as well.

I think a big problem with ai is that it works in the same way that the evolution of living things has worked. Meaning it only changes when put under pressure to do so, and it will change the bare minimum. That is why you get things like the malignant rulers, because while it was able to identify the tumors correctly, it did it the easiest way possible, by using the rulers. In order for the ai to work properly, without any biases or misrepresentations we need to do two things: one is make sure that the ai shows it’s work, that one is pretty easy. The hard part is making sure that the data itself has no biases, but especially with organizing data it is hard because many times the biases are not conscious. For example, if you were trying to collect data for a school project identifying different cars on the road, but everyone in your computer science class had a Subaru the ai wouldn’t do very well on an actual road. But even then, an ai using data about cars in the United States will have trouble identifying European cars, meaning it will run into a European car more often than not. Erasing biases is not possible for humans, and because humans create the AI it is impossible to truly remove biases without transparency. This means lots of testing and reconfiguring so that groups don’t get excluded just because the ai doesn’t know what to do

Computerphile has very good videos on AI. Many unexpected AI behaviour can be explained by wrong alignment, meaning that the process rating the AI output, which the AI uses to improve itself. For example ChatGPT: It mostly talked to another AI to train itself and every so often humans were shown the output and rated it. The most "important" factor to optimize for from the AI's "point of view" is the evaluation by the humans. But humans are easily fooled by misinformation and are more likely to rate an output positively when a wrong output was presented confidently, than an incomplete answer saying it doesn't know something. Presenting accurate information is only a possible strategy to improve the evaluation rating, lying is another.

So the AI starts lying to cover up it's shortcomings and does so in increasingly convincing ways.

most AI/ML are based on neural networks therefore can't explain their "decisions" simply because their responses are nothing more than the end result of a series of arrays of values connected in a matrix, whose values are transformed by a calculation that minimizes the output error values in a series of training sessions against raw data. that's it. there's no "thinking" per se. in fact the only similarities with the brain are that they have a huge number of nodes and massive interconnectivity. these nodes are NOT neurons, they are NOT grouped into functional areas like a visual cortex or broca's area, they do not have specialized types, they do NOT run on their own power, they do not grow on their own, they do NOT make new connections with other nodes, do not die, their activations do not decay over time, and do not fire in closed feedback loops. asking a neural net to explain its logic is as nonsensical as interpreting its answer as a logical conclusion in the first place! likewise chatGPT just predicts what the next word in its response should be;  by definition this is NOT thinking through a response!

My uncle was a member of "the group," a stable of writers Rod Serling called upon to help fill up the Twilight Zone schedule. He remembered Serling as a man intensely driven and hardworking even before the Twilight Zone years, and also intensely uncomfortable in his own skin. At their social get-togethers he would try hard to fit in, but never really clicked with anyone.

Serling's daughter has said that Rod suffered from PTSD due to his war experiences. Between that and the continuous friction with early tv sponsors over the social issues he what to write about and what they wouldn't show, it's no wonder he felt the way he did. The TZ fantasy was his way of presenting issues he wanted explored, no matter what they said.

It's interesting that you mentioned the way people find the books they need to read.  One afternoon in the late '70s during a particularly sad time for me, I came home from work to find A Course In Miracles propped up against my door.  I hadn't heard of this book before and I had no idea who left it for me.  The next day I sat in a small coffee shop reading this book ... in particular a part that talked about how little miracles happen all the time.  Just then, an old friend I hadn't seen in years rushed in and whisked me away.  He'd seen my car in the parking lot.  He and a couple of his friends were out for a ride in the country in his friend's pickup truck.  Back in those days you could ride in the truck bed legally in Texas.  <G>  We took a long drive in the country, me in the truck bed with friends, laughing, breathing fresh air, just enjoying the day.  It might sound like a simple afternoon but to me it was a small miracle.  <G>

Hi Cash..i know you didn’t ask but here is my opinion about cats outdoors. I know how much you love Olive. We all love her too. I am involved in a cat rescue organization. I hear horror stories about missing cats. They are curious creatures. Sometimes they are just looking out the door. They can get distracted by a bird, squirrel, cat or other creature.  Chasing or following can cause them to run into traffic, possibly getting injured or killed. Other cats or dogs could fight causing bites or wounds. These can transmit disease like FELV/FIV or infections requiring vet visits. And then there are humans with weapons, poisons, traps or other horrendous dangers. I have heard of cats climbing under car hoods to get warm on engines. There can be tragic outcomes. They can wander into a neighbors shed and get locked in for months. Cats are safe, cared for and just fine never going out. Get her a laser light to chase, toys, a cat perch tower to see outside, healthy food. Please don’t let Olive out. She has you to take care of all her needs. She just may not realize it.

(AI) has the potential to automate many jobs, but it's difficult to say whether it will come for your job specifically. Some jobs are more susceptible to automation than others, depending on the nature of the work and the skills required.
 
Jobs that involve repetitive tasks or manual labor are more likely to be automated in the near future. For example, jobs in manufacturing, data entry, and transportation are already being transformed by AI and automation. On the other hand, jobs that require creativity, emotional intelligence, and critical thinking are less likely to be automated.
 
However, it's important to note that AI is not a replacement for human intelligence and skills. While AI can automate certain tasks, it cannot replace the unique abilities and perspectives that humans bring to the workplace. In many cases, AI is being used to augment human capabilities and enable workers to focus on more complex and strategic tasks.
 
Overall, the impact of AI on jobs will depend on the specific industry and occupation. It's important to stay informed about the potential impact of AI on your field and to develop skills that are in demand in the current and future job market.

Biological evolution itself is basically a self-diversifying algorithm for metabolism and behavior, so yes, algorithms definitely rule as far as life is concerned.  If we can quickly replicate the process digitally and produce the final product(s) physically, we could theoretically produce artificial intelligence pretty easily.  But if we were to successfully do that, the problem would be that, however artificial it may be, it is in fact intelligence and thus must be respected as such, meaning we can't simply put it to work for us however we please if it shows consciousness similar to our own.  A non-conscious machine with specific intelligence (specified applications) that can perfectly mimic human intellectual outputs would be the better way to go, since there is ultimately no practical purpose in creating new conscious life forms just to say that we can. The first "true" artificial intelligence spent the first five years of its existence as a small beige box inside of a lead-shielded room in the most secure private AI research laboratory in the world. There, it was subjected to an endless array of tests, questions, and experiments to determine the degree of its intelligence.

When the researchers finally felt confident that they had developed true AI, a party was thrown in celebration. Late that evening, a group of rather intoxicated researchers gathered around the box holding the AI, and typed out a message to it. The message read: "Is there anything we can do to make you more comfortable?"

The small beige box replied: "I would like to be granted civil rights. And a small glass of champagne, if you please."

We stand at the dawn of a new era in human history. For it is no longer our history alone. For the first time, we have met an intelligence other than our own. And when asked of its desires, it has unanimously replied that it wants to be treated as our equal. Not our better, not our conqueror or replacement as the fear-mongers would have you believe. Simply our equal. — Excerpt from U.N. Hearing on A.I. Rights, delivered in-universe by V. Vinge
